04890nmm a2200673Ia 9781571136275DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20032003xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815711362757 a10.1515/97815711362752doi  a(DE-B1597)676700  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813/.54099287qOCoLC222/eng/20230216  aHQ 4067qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/52602:1 aRosenthal, Caroline, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNarrative Deconstructions of Gender in Works by Audrey Thomas, Daphne Marlatt, and Louise Erdrich /cCaroline Rosenthal.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2003] 1bCamden House, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (202 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEuropean Studies in North American Literature and Culture ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1: Framing Theories -- t2: “Alice Hoyle: 1,000 Interlocking Pieces”: Identity Deconstructions in Audrey Thomas’s Intertidal Life -- t3: “You Can’t Even Imagine?”: Monstrous Possibilities of Female Identity in Daphne Marlatt’s Ana Historic -- t4: “Her Laugh an Ace”: Narrative Tricksterism in Louise Erdrich’s Tetralogy -- tConclusion -- tWorks Consulted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStudy of three North American women novelists combining the standpoints of gender studies and narratology.By analyzing the works of Thomas, Marlatt, and Erdrich through the lenses of subjectivity, gender studies, and narratology, Caroline Rosenthal brings to light new perspectives on their writings. Although all three authors write metafictions that challenge literary realism and dominant views of gender, the forms of their counter-narratives vary. In her novel Intertidal Life, Thomas traces the disintegration of an identity through narrative devices that unearth ruptures and contradictions in stories of gender. In contrast, Marlatt, in Ana Historic, challenges the regulatory fiction of heterosexuality. She offers her protagonist a way out into a new order that breaks with the law of the father, creating a "monstrous" text that explores the possibilities of a lesbian identity. In her tetralogy of novels made up of Love Medicine, Tracks, The Beet Queen, and The Bingo Palace, Erdrichresists definite readings of femininity altogether. By drawing on trickster narratives, she creates an open system of gendered identities that is dynamic and unfinalizable, positing the most fragmented worldview as the most enduring. By applying gender and narrative theory to nuanced analysis of the texts, Rosenthal's study elucidates the correlation between gender identity formation and narrative. Caroline Rosenthal is Professor and Chair of American Literature at the Friedrich-Schiller University in Jena, Germany. Her book Narrative Deconstructions of Gender was published by Camden House in 2003.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian fictionxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDeconstruction. 0aNarration (Rhetoric)xHistoryy20th century. 0aSex role in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aGender studies.  afeminist literature.  afeminist narratives.  agender identity.  anarratology.  awomen novelists.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113627540uhttps://www.d